15 September 2019 at 10:18 am

The attitude in the article discussed above, from a properly researched study, is significant. It is an intensely local and culturally determined attitude, and fundamentally different from the US reticence on abortion -even for religious reasons, regardless of genetics concerned.

This would be more usefully known than the nonsensical Hong Kong 'worldwide civilisation' talk in all its endless iterations. That fugue has run its blasphemous course and needs to be stopped. The likelihood that it will, clearly diminishes with each repetition.

Neither side is motivated by political legitimacy. Beijing don't care about Hong Kong's legal system/constitutional order and the anti-authoritarian stance of the Umbrella movement. The Hong Kong protestors are tearing down cultural heritage and setting a dangerous on-going trend for mob rule. They're a symptom of Westerners' sense of epistemic entitlement caused by a slow drip feed of feel-good journalism. The US trade war is the real 'green light'.

Like I said, the article wasn't significantly motivated by political legitimacy. It was responding to the conspicuous absence of what might loosely be described "purple print
